                <head>No. 403.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Davis</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">De Long</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1873-08-21">
                            <hi rend="italic">August</hi> 21, 1873</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 212.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to your No. 439, of the 5th ultimo, in
                    which inquiry is made as to whether a citizen of the United States residing in
                    Japan is at liberty to surrender to that government his privileges of
                    extraterritoriality, I have to state in answer that, as an American, he cannot
                    alter treaties existing between the two countries, but he can expatriate himself
                    if he wishes so to do.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>J. C. B. DAVIS,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
